            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this PAYE UK calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool gives a clear, step‑by‑step estimate of your PAYE
                deductions based on the standard rules for the 2024/25 tax year
                in England, Wales and Northern Ireland.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Convert your pay to an annual figure</h3>
              <p>
                Whatever pay frequency you choose, the calculator first converts
                it to an annual amount:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Annual pay</strong> =</p>
                <ul class="list-disc ml-5">
                  <li><em>Annual</em>: your input</li>
                  <li><em>Monthly</em>: input × 12</li>
                  <li><em>Weekly</em>: input × 52</li>
                  <li><em>4‑weekly</em>: input × 13</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Apply pension contributions (salary sacrifice style)</h3>
              <p>
                If you enter a pension percentage, we assume it is taken from
                gross pay before tax and NIC (similar to salary sacrifice):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Pension = Annual pay × (pension % ÷ 100)</p>
                <p>Taxable pay = Annual pay − Pension</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Personal allowance and income tax bands (2024/25)</h3>
              <p>
                For a standard 1257L tax code, the personal allowance is
                £12,570. This calculator assumes the full allowance unless you
                enter a non‑standard code (in which case it adjusts the
                allowance from the numeric part of the code).
              </p>
              <p>Income tax bands used (rest of UK):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Personal allowance:</strong> 0% on the first £12,570
                  (if fully available)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Basic rate:</strong> 20% on £12,571 – £50,270</li>
                <li><strong>Higher rate:</strong> 40% on £50,271 – £125,140</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Additional rate:</strong> 45% on income above £125,140
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For simplicity, this tool does not taper the personal allowance
                for incomes above £100,000 (in reality it is reduced by £1 for
                every £2 above that level). That means very high earners will
                see slightly lower tax here than in reality.
              </p>

              <h3>4. National Insurance (Class 1 employee)</h3>
              <p>
                For employees under State Pension age we use the main Class 1
                NIC thresholds for 2024/25:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Primary threshold (PT):</strong> £12,570 per year –
                  below this, no employee NIC
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Upper earnings limit (UEL):</strong> £50,270 per year
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Employee NIC rates (simplified):</p>
              <ul>
                <li>8% on earnings between PT and UEL</li>
                <li>2% on earnings above UEL</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you select “Over State Pension age”, employee NIC is set to
                £0.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Student loan repayments</h3>
              <p>
                If you choose a student loan plan, the calculator applies the
                relevant threshold and rate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Plan 1:</strong> 9% above £24,990</li>
                <li><strong>Plan 2:</strong> 9% above £27,295</li>
                <li><strong>Plan 4 (Scotland):</strong> 9% above £31,395</li>
                <li><strong>Plan 5:</strong> 9% above £25,000</li>
                <li><strong>Postgraduate loan:</strong> 6% above £21,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These thresholds are approximate and rounded for clarity; HMRC
                may update them each tax year.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Employer National Insurance (optional)</h3>
              <p>
                If you toggle on “Show employer NIC”, the calculator estimates
                employer Class 1 NIC using a single main rate and threshold:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Secondary threshold:</strong> £9,100 per year</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Employer NIC rate:</strong> 13.8% above that threshold
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This does not affect your take‑home pay, but it shows the total
                cost of employing you.
              </p>

              <h3>7. Net pay and effective tax rate</h3>
              <p>Finally, we compute:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  Total deductions = Income tax + Employee NIC + Pension +
                  Student loan
                </p>
                <p>Net pay = Gross pay − Total deductions</p>
                <p>Effective deduction rate = Total deductions ÷ Gross pay</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Example: PAYE on a £35,000 salary</h2>
              <p>
                Assumptions: annual salary £35,000, standard 1257L tax code, 5%
                pension, no student loan, under State Pension age.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Annual gross pay: £35,000</li>
                <li>Pension (5%): £1,750 → taxable pay £33,250</li>
                <li>Income tax: 20% on £20,680 (33,250 − 12,570) ≈ £4,136</li>
                <li>Employee NIC: 8% on (£35,000 − 12,570) ≈ £1,792</li>
                <li>Total deductions ≈ £1,750 + £4,136 + £1,792 = £7,678</li>
                <li>Net annual pay ≈ £27,322 (about £2,277 per month)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Your own results will update instantly as you adjust the inputs.
              </p>

              <h2>Understanding PAYE in the UK</h2>
              <p>
                PAYE (Pay As You Earn) is the system HMRC uses to collect income
                tax and National Insurance from most employees and pensioners.
                Instead of paying a big tax bill at the end of the year, tax is
                deducted from your wages or pension each time you are paid.
              </p>

              <h3>Key parts of PAYE</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tax code:</strong> tells your employer how much
                  tax‑free allowance to give you.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Income tax:</strong> charged in bands (basic, higher,
                  additional rate).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>National Insurance:</strong> separate from income tax,
                  funds state benefits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Other deductions:</strong> pension, student loans,
                  child maintenance, etc.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>When this calculator is most useful</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Checking a new job offer to see your likely take‑home pay.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Comparing full‑time vs part‑time or contracting vs employment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Planning pension contributions and understanding their impact
                  on net pay.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Getting a quick sense of how much PAYE tax and NIC you pay
                  each year.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about PAYE</h2>

              <h3>Is PAYE the same as income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                Not exactly. PAYE is the <em>system</em> used to collect income
                tax (and NIC) from your pay. Income tax is the actual tax you
                owe on your income.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I still need to do a Self Assessment tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                Many employees do not need to file a Self Assessment return if
                all their income is taxed through PAYE and HMRC has the right
                information. You may need to file if you are self‑employed, have
                significant untaxed income, high income with certain benefits,
                or are a company director. Check HMRC guidance if you are
                unsure.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my tax code is wrong?</h3>
              <p>
                If you think your tax code is incorrect, you should contact HMRC
                or check your Personal Tax Account online. A wrong code can mean
                you pay too much or too little tax through PAYE. This calculator
                lets you experiment with different codes to see the impact on
                your allowance and net pay.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator official?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an independent educational tool based on publicly
                available PAYE rules. For official guidance and personalised
                information, always refer to HMRC or a qualified tax adviser.
              </p>
